'''Willie "The Wisp" Fleming''' (born [[February 2]], [[1939]] in [[Detroit, Michigan]]) is a former professional [[Canadian football]] player with the [[Canadian Football League]] [[British Columbia Lions]].  Fleming played [[college football|collegiately]] as a [[Running back|halfback]] at the [[University of Iowa]], where he was a member of the [[Iowa Hawkeyes|Hawkeye's]] [[1958 Iowa Hawkeyes football team#Rose Bowl|1959 Rose Bowl championship team]].  He is a member of the [[Canadian Football Hall of Fame]], the [[B.C. Sports Hall of Fame]], and the [[British Columbia Lions#BC Lions Wall of Fame at BC Place Stadium|B.C. Lions Wall of Fame]]. Fleming's #15 jersey is one of eight numbers [[B.C. Lions#Retired Numbers|retired]] by the Lions.<ref name="B.C. Lions Retired Numbers (B.C. Lions)">{{cite web | url = http://www.bclions.com/index.php?module=page&id=3066 | accessdate = 2006-08-20 | title = B.C. Lions Retired Numbers | publisher = BCLions.com}}</ref> In 2003, Fleming was voted a member of the [[British Columbia Lions#2004 50th Anniversary Dream Team (as selected by the fans)|B.C. Lions All-Time Dream Team]] as part of the club<U+2019>s 50 year anniversary celebration.<ref name="B.C. Lions Dream Team">{{cite web | url = http://www.bclions.com/index.php?module=page&id=3060 | accessdate = 2006-09-10 | title = B.C. Lions Dream Team | publisher = BCLions.com}}</ref> In 2006, Fleming was voted to the Honour Roll of the CFL's [[TSN Top 50 CFL Players|Top 50 players]] of the league's modern era by Canadian sports network [[The Sports Network|TSN]].<ref name="TSN Top 50 Honour Roll">{{cite web | url = http://www.tsn.ca/cfl/feature/?fid=10855 | accessdate = 2007-05-01 | author = | title = TSN Top 50 Honour Roll | publisher = TSN.ca | date = 2006-11-28}}</ref>

Fleming earned the nickname, "The Wisp" or "Will 'o the Wisp," because of his elusive running style.<ref name="Canadian Football Hall of Fame: Willie Fleming">{{cite web | url = http://www.footballhof.com/famers/player.asp?id=80 | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | author = | title = Canadian Football Hall of Fame: Willie Fleming | publisher = Canadian Football Hall of Fame & Museum | date = 1982}}</ref>

== High School and College Career ==
Fleming played halfback in [[High school football|high school]] in his native Detroit, winning All-City honors in 1956.  In 1957, Fleming began his college career at the [[University of Iowa]], where he was eventually named an [[Associated Press]] First Team All-[[Big Ten]] player in 1958.  In [[1958 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|1958]], Fleming helped the Hawkeyes to a 6-0-1 Big Ten clinching victory over the [[University of Minnesota]], and led [[1958 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|the team]] in scoring.<ref name="Top Ten (College Football)">{{cite web | url = http://jcgi.pathfinder.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,810670,00.html | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | author = || title = Top Ten (College Football) | publisher = ''TIME.com''| date = 1958-11-17}}</ref><ref name="2005 Iowa Hawkeye's Football Media Guide - Year-by-Year Scoring Records">{{cite web | url = http://graphics.fansonly.com/photos/schools/iowa/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/0506-supplement.pdf | accessdate = 2006-09-05 | title = 2005 Iowa Hawkeye's Football Media Guide - Year-by-Year Scoring Records | date = 2005}}</ref>

In 1959, Fleming and the 7-1-1 Hawkeyes defeated the [[University of California, Berkeley|University of California]] (and Fleming's future B.C. Lions teammate, [[quarterback]] [[Joe Kapp]]) 38-12, in the [[1958 Iowa Hawkeyes football team#Rose Bowl|1959 Rose Bowl]].<ref name="Rose Bowl Game Photo Timeline: 1950-1959">{{cite web | url = http://www.tournamentofroses.com/photogallery/RBGtimeline/1950sb.htm | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | author = | title = Rose Bowl Game Photo Timeline: 1950-1959 | publisher = Pasadena Tournament of Roses | date = }}</ref> Fleming scored 2 [[Rush (American football)|rushing]] [[touchdowns]] in the game, and finished with 85 yards on 9 attempts.<ref name="2005 Iowa Hawkeye's Football Media Guide - Iowa Bowl History (1959 Rose Bowl)">{{cite web | url = http://graphics.fansonly.com/photos/schools/iowa/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/0506-supplement.pdf | accessdate = 2006-09-05 | title = 2005 Iowa Hawkeye's Football Media Guide - Iowa Bowl History (1959 Rose Bowl) | date = 2005}}</ref>

== Professional career ==
Following the 1959 Rose Bowl, Fleming joined the [[Canadian Football League]] [[B.C. Lions]] for the [[1959 CFL season|1959 season]].  By [[1960 CFL season|1960]], he became the first Lion to eclipse 1,000 yards rushing with 1,051 yards on 125 carries for an 8.4 yard average.<ref name="CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions)">{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/cfl_historical/Fleming.Willie.htm | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions) | publisher = CFL:  A Historical Look (Fan Site)}}</ref> 

In [[1963 CFL season|1963]], Fleming and Kapp led the Lions to a 12-4 record and the [[Canadian Football League West Division|CFL Western Division]] championship.<ref name="CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions)">{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/cfl_historical/Fleming.Willie.htm | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions) | publisher = CFL:  A Historical Look (Fan Site)}}</ref> The Lions next faced the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] in the 1963 CFL Championship [[Grey Cup]].  During the [[1963 Grey Cup]] game, Fleming was involved in a widely discussed and controversial play as he was hit by Ti-Cat [[defensive lineman]] [[Angelo Mosca]], allegedly while Fleming was out of bounds, resulting in Fleming's absence from the remainder of the game (and a trip to the hospital).<ref name="CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions)">{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/cfl_historical/Fleming.Willie.htm | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions) | publisher = CFL:  A Historical Look (Fan Site)}}</ref><ref name="BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming">{{cite web | url = http://www.bcsportshalloffame.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi?person_id=53&stype=searchname&keyword=fleming&type=ind&sport_id=41&year_=2006&category_id=team | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming | publisher = BC Sports Hall of Fame.com}}</ref> Despite a disappointing end to the season (the Lions lost to the Tiger-Cats, 21-10), Fleming had his finest season as a professional football player, as he rushed for 1,234 yards on 127 carries for an incredible 9.7 yard average.<ref name="CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions)">{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/cfl_historical/Fleming.Willie.htm | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = CFL:  A Historical Look - Willie Fleming (B.C. Lions) | publisher = CFL:  A Historical Look (Fan Site)}}</ref>

The following year, Fleming and the Lions would get their revenge, as the B.C. Lions again faced the Hamilton Tiger-Cats in the [[1964 Grey Cup]].  The [[British Columbia Lions#The 1964 Grey Cup Champions|Lions won their first CFL championship]] 34-24, and Fleming scored a game-breaking touchdown on a 68 yard scoring run over Mosca's position.<ref name="BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming">{{cite web | url = http://www.bcsportshalloffame.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi?person_id=53&stype=searchname&keyword=fleming&type=ind&sport_id=41&year_=2006&category_id=team | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming | publisher = BC Sports Hall of Fame.com}}</ref> Earlier in the [[1964 CFL season|1964 season]], Fleming scored the longest touchdown run from scrimmage (109 yards) against the [[Edmonton Eskimos]], a CFL record that still stands.<ref name="Rings of Glory">{{cite web | url = http://www.vancourier.com/issues06/081106/news/081106nn1.html | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | author = Corben, Len || title = Rings of Glory | publisher = ''Vancouver Courier''| date = 2006-08-02}}</ref>

Fleming retired from the CFL and the B.C. Lions following the [[1966 CFL season|1966 season]].  Fleming retired as a [[1963 CFL season#1963 CFL All-Stars|CFL All-Star in 1963]], a three-time [[Canadian Football League West Division|CFL Western Division]] All-Star, and was named the most popular B.C. Lions Player three times.  Fleming was inducted into the [[Canadian Football Hall of Fame]] in 1982.<ref name="BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming">{{cite web | url = http://www.bcsportshalloffame.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi?person_id=53&stype=searchname&keyword=fleming&type=ind&sport_id=41&year_=2006&category_id=team | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | title = BC Sports Hall of Fame - Willie Fleming | publisher = BC Sports Hall of Fame.com}}</ref> In [[2003 CFL season|2003]], Fleming was voted a member of the [[British Columbia Lions#2004 50th Anniversary Dream Team (as selected by the fans)|B.C. Lions All-Time Dream Team]], at the [[running back|running back position]], as part of the club<U+2019>s 50 year anniversary celebration.<ref name="B.C. Lions Dream Team">{{cite web | url = http://www.bclions.com/index.php?module=page&id=3060 | accessdate = 2006-09-10 | title = B.C. Lions Dream Team | publisher = BCLions.com}}</ref> In [[November]], [[2006 CFL season|2006]], Fleming was voted to the Honour Roll of the CFL's top 50 players of the league's modern era by Canadian sports network [[The Sports Network|TSN]].<ref name="TSN Top 50 Honour Roll">{{cite web | url = http://www.tsn.ca/cfl/feature/?fid=10855 | accessdate = 2007-05-01 | author = | title = TSN Top 50 Honour Roll | publisher = TSN.ca | date = 2006-11-28}}</ref>

== Post-Football Life ==
Retired from the [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] since [[1967 CFL season|1967]], Fleming currently resides in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref name="Rings of Glory">{{cite web | url = http://www.vancourier.com/issues06/081106/news/081106nn1.html | accessdate = 2006-08-26 | author = Corben, Len || title = Rings of Glory | publisher = ''Vancouver Courier''| date = 2006-08-02}}</ref>

